Data: monthly bond and equity flows (they seem OUTFLOWS) from the U.S. to 55 countries, from January 1988 to November 2013.

Theories: standard economic fundamentals

Methodology: Bayesian dynamic latent MULTIFACTOR model (THREE types of latent persistent factors: global, asset-specific, country-specific) is flexible but high-dimensional (397 parameters to estimate), panel unit-root tests, time series to explain global factors, panel to explain the push factor.

Results: global (not domestic) factors are the primary drivers of international portfolio flows (explain more than 80{\%} of their variance - Table 2), little relative contribution of regional factors - Table 3. During the crisis "the global component of the push factor increases its contribution." Economic variables explains 1/4 of the variation in the push and pull factors. The push factor is associated with U.S. economic variables (industrial gap, 10 yr yield, US/World stock return, dVIX, TED), and the pull factors by domestic ones (industrial gap, 10 yr yield, stock return, Chinn-Ito, lagged pull factor). 

Conclusion: capital controls may be more effective than macroeconomic policies for managing capital flows.

