Results: heterogeneity in the variance of capital flows explained by common factor among countries. Three groups: sensitive, asymmetric, insensitive.

Push factors explain most of the variation in the common factor but their importance varies by type of flow.

To explain the variability in the betas (factor loadings), the correlation of the flows with the investor base (EPFR, BIS) play a more important role than macro fundamentals. i.e. EM sensitivity to push factors is mainly driven by investor base rather than macro fundamentals.

They find that the countries with higher betas are associated with deeper retrenchments in flows during GFC and the taper tantrum.

Side in debate. Quote: "good fundamentals do not assure a country's insulation from global financial shocks" p. 18
Thus collect information about your lenders (foreign investor base).},
